<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Health Select Committee Inquiry into Public Health England</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Denplan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (PHE001</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We would like to commend the mandate and work of Public Heath England to date in exploring ways to improve the public’s health by working with other organisations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The dental profession can play an important role in helping Public Health England to tackle chronic conditions through prevention, early intervention and advice for patients on oral health. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England can achieve its objectives in part by fostering partnership working across dental teams, health and wellbeing boards and primary care.  Its initial work towards this end is encouraging.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This approach should not only facilitate continued improvements in oral health and its related diseases, but also support the public to protect and improve its own general health and wellbeing.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Supporting information:</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The establishment of Public Health England presents a significant opportunity to improve the nation’s health, address inequalities and raise the profile of other key challenges to wellbeing by developing a national framework that is implementable locally.  This can be furthered not only by ensuring better access to quality care but also to information that will assist patients in making positive decisions about their health and wellbeing.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The development of wider partnerships and collaborative working across key professional stakeholders will play an important function in Public Health England achieving a positive outcome.  This will inevitably involve coordinated activities with NHS England, clinical commissioning groups and health and wellbeing boards.  It should also aim to engage a broader set of stakeholders and disciplines.  Dentistry is one example.  The dental profession has a significant, skilled workforce in private, independent and NHS practice that can be harnessed to meet Britain’s public health challenge.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is appropriate given the scale of the challenge, including the connection between public health and chronic disease.  Around two-thirds of the money for health and social care is spent on long term conditions which affect 15 million people currently living in Britain, a number projected to grow significantly in the next 10 years.  By 2018 it is anticipated that 2.9 million will be living with three or more long term conditions.  Preventing the on-flow and the causes of long term conditions is critical to Britain’s health and wellbeing, and alleviating extra pressure on the NHS and local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In many respects dentistry and public health share a common agenda.  Public Health England’s focus on obesity, diet, smoking and alcohol links with good oral health, and dentistry can help detect a number of chronic conditions that these can generate.  For example:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dental problems are more common in people with diabetes.  It is estimated that people with Type 2 diabetes are three times more likely to develop dental problems than people without diabetes, and the risk is also increased for people with Type 1.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Medical research has found a correlation between atherosclerotic (cardiovascular and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cerebrovascular</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> disease: notably heart attack and stroke) and periodontal disease (gum disease).  43% of the UK population suffer from periodontal disease, costing £2.73bn last year.  A BMJ study (May 2010) found a 70% increased risk of cardiovascular disease event among those who did not brush their teeth twice a day. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Now studies have shown that kidneys, like other major organs, are at a similar risk to be affected by periodontal disease through bacteria in the blood stream.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since up to one million patients visit a dentist each week, dentists are well-placed to detect and advise upon tobacco consumption, alcohol usage and diet and where appropriate signpost to relevant services.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The dental profession can therefore help Public Health England improve the nation’s health and encourage positive behaviours that jointly benefit good oral health and good general health.  This in turn relates to the prevention of, and earlier intervention in long term conditions.   Helping people think about and manage their own health on a daily basis will be an important part of the Public Health England’s success and rising to the long term conditions challenge.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England’s health check programme, which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">aims to help prevent heart disease, stroke, diabetes and kidney disease, is a good tool in encouraging people to access services locally, such as their dentist.  As noted above, many of the diseases the tool seeks to prevent have strong links with oral health and can be diagnosed or prevented through dentistry.  Better establishing these links and utilising the programme to that end will support that further.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Denplan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> Excel accredited dentists, for example, undertake </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evidence-based oral health and disease</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">risk assessments</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for each patient.  This complements Public Heath England’s work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Enabling dentistry to play a full and proper part in public health locally will be important in achieving Public Health England’s goals.  Initial signs that this may happen have been positive.  But it needs to be built upon consistently in order to promote healthy lifestyles, protect oral health and prevent or better manage emergence of long term conditions.  Welcoming the dental profession in its widest sense to participate in local health forums, planning and prevention offers potential results for local people, the NHS and Public Health England.  We would encourage local authorities, health and wellbeing boards, NHS England and Public Health England to continue to embrace and extend that interaction.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Denplan</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Denplan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is the UK’s leading dental payment specialist with over 6,500 members across the UK and approximately 1.8 million patients.  Founded in 1986, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Denplan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> created a system that allowed dentists to spend more time with their patients, focusing on preventative oral healthcare and providing high quality treatment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Denplan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would be pleased to answer any questions that the committee has on this short submission in advance of its hearing for this inquiry.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>